iter123 (2026-05-27): defense-in-depth for the nested-spool storm. ROOT CAUSE confirmed: in/prd-resolve/.gm/exec-spool/{in,out} is EMPTY dirs only - a misrooted recursive mkdir (a process treating in/prd-resolve as a project root). The storm fires only when a watcher WALKS those + derives verb=prd-resolve/.gm/exec-spool/in (path-separator verb) -> bogus outName -> ENOENT every tick. iter121 walkDir dot-skip prevents the walk. ADDED defense-in-depth: processFile now skips+unmarks any file whose derived verb contains a path separator or dot-segment (a real verb is a single clean segment), so even if a future walk reaches such a file it dispatch-skips with a spool.skip-nested-verb event instead of ENOENT-storming. Two layers now: walkDir won-t reach them, processFile won-t dispatch them. LESSON: derive-verb-from-path needs validation that the result is a single clean segment; never trust the path shape.